INSERT INTO comprension_texts (subject_id, level, grades, title, text_content, questions) VALUES
('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Climate Change and the Future of the Planet', 'Climate change is one of the most serious challenges facing humanity in the twenty-first century. Scientific evidence gathered over decades shows that the Earth is warming at an unprecedented rate, mostly due to human activities. Since the Industrial Revolution, the burning of fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and gas has released enormous amounts of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases into the atmosphere. These gases trap heat from the sun and cause global temperatures to rise. The consequences are already visible: melting glaciers, rising sea levels, more intense heatwaves, droughts, and extreme weather events. Ecosystems around the world are being disrupted, and many species face the threat of extinction. The impact on human societies is also significant, with millions of people forced to migrate from their homes because of natural disasters or the loss of agricultural land. In response, international agreements such as the Paris Agreement of 2015 have set ambitious goals to limit global warming, encouraging countries to reduce their emissions and invest in renewable energy. At the individual level, small changes in daily habits, such as using public transport, saving energy, or reducing food waste, can also make a difference. The fight against climate change requires cooperation between governments, businesses, and citizens, and time is of the essence, because the decisions taken in the coming years will determine the quality of life of future generations.', '[{"pregunta":"What is the main cause of climate change?","opciones":["Volcanic eruptions","Human activities burning fossil fuels","Solar cycles","Ocean currents"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which agreement was signed in 2015?","opciones":["Kyoto Protocol","Paris Agreement","Rio Declaration","Montreal Protocol"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which is NOT mentioned as a consequence?","opciones":["Melting glaciers","Rising sea levels","Better harvests everywhere","Droughts"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"What can individuals do to help?","opciones":["Nothing","Change daily habits","Ignore the problem","Consume more"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The History of the English Language', 'The English language has an extraordinary history that reflects the many peoples and cultures that have influenced it over the centuries. English belongs to the Germanic branch of the Indo-European family, and its earliest form, known as Old English, was brought to Britain by Germanic tribes from the fifth century onwards. It was very different from modern English and is considered a separate language by most linguists. The Norman Conquest in 1066 introduced thousands of French words into the vocabulary, especially in areas like law, administration, and cuisine. This period led to what is called Middle English, the language of Geoffrey Chaucer and The Canterbury Tales. From the late fifteenth century, Early Modern English began to develop. The invention of the printing press, the Renaissance, and the plays of William Shakespeare contributed to the standardisation and enrichment of the language. The Industrial Revolution and the expansion of the British Empire spread English across the world, making it the global language of trade, science, and communication. Today, more than one and a half billion people use English as a first or second language, and the language continues to change rapidly, borrowing vocabulary from many sources and being shaped by new technologies and social media. Its long history reminds us that languages are living entities that constantly evolve with the societies that speak them.', '[{"pregunta":"Which event introduced many French words to English?","opciones":["The Roman Empire","The Norman Conquest","The Renaissance","The Industrial Revolution"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Who wrote The Canterbury Tales?","opciones":["Shakespeare","Chaucer","Milton","Dickens"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What helped standardise Early Modern English?","opciones":["Television","The printing press","The internet","Steam engines"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"About how many people use English today?","opciones":["500 million","800 million","1 billion","Over 1.5 billion"],"correcta":3}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Benefits of Reading Books', 'In a time when screens dominate our daily lives, reading books remains one of the most valuable activities for personal growth. Numerous studies have shown that regular reading offers a wide range of benefits for the mind and the emotions. First, it strengthens vocabulary and improves writing skills, as readers are constantly exposed to different styles and rich expressions. Second, it enhances concentration and memory, since following a long story or an argument requires focus and retention of details. Third, reading literature helps develop empathy by allowing readers to enter the minds of characters whose experiences may be very different from their own. It also reduces stress: research has found that just a few minutes of reading can significantly lower heart rate and muscle tension. Beyond these practical benefits, books open doors to new worlds, broaden perspectives, and stimulate critical thinking. Whether fiction or non-fiction, books challenge us to question, to imagine, and to learn. In educational contexts, students who read regularly tend to perform better academically, not only in language subjects but also in others. Despite the appeal of digital entertainment, books continue to play an essential role in personal and intellectual development. Encouraging young people to read for pleasure is one of the best investments a society can make in its future, and public libraries, schools, and families all have a role to play in making reading a lifelong habit.', '[{"pregunta":"Which is NOT a mentioned benefit of reading?","opciones":["Vocabulary","Concentration","Physical strength","Empathy"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"How does reading affect stress?","opciones":["It increases it","It has no effect","It can lower it","It causes insomnia"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"What do readers develop by entering characters'' minds?","opciones":["Muscles","Empathy","Speed","Memory only"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Who should encourage reading according to the text?","opciones":["Only teachers","Only parents","Libraries, schools, and families","Only publishers"],"correcta":2}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Artificial Intelligence in Everyday Life', 'Artificial intelligence, often shortened to AI, has become a part of everyday life in ways many people do not even notice. When you unlock your phone with facial recognition, receive personalised film suggestions on a streaming platform, or ask a virtual assistant about the weather, you are interacting with AI. These systems rely on algorithms that can analyse enormous amounts of data and learn from patterns. Machine learning, a branch of AI, enables computers to improve their performance without being explicitly programmed for every task. The applications are already transforming many fields. In medicine, AI helps to diagnose diseases from medical images with remarkable precision. In transport, self-driving cars use AI to interpret their environment and make decisions. In business, AI powers recommendation systems, customer service chatbots, and fraud detection. However, the rapid spread of AI also raises serious concerns. Privacy, bias in decisions made by algorithms, the future of employment, and the ethics of autonomous systems are some of the most debated issues. Experts agree that the development of AI should be guided by clear rules and human values, ensuring that the technology benefits society as a whole rather than a small group. Understanding how AI works and what its limits are is therefore essential for all citizens, because the decisions we take now will shape the role that artificial intelligence plays in the future of humanity.', '[{"pregunta":"What is machine learning?","opciones":["A new programming language","A branch of AI where computers improve with data","A type of robot","A smartphone app"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which field is NOT mentioned as using AI?","opciones":["Medicine","Transport","Business","Traditional farming without technology"],"correcta":3},{"pregunta":"What is a concern raised by AI?","opciones":["Bias in algorithmic decisions","Too much free time","Cheap food","Reduced internet speed"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What should guide the development of AI?","opciones":["Profit only","Clear rules and human values","Secrecy","Random chance"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Importance of Bilingualism', 'Bilingualism, the ability to speak two languages fluently, is becoming more common in an increasingly interconnected world. Many children grow up speaking two languages from birth, while others learn a second language at school or later in life. Whatever the route, knowing more than one language brings significant advantages. From a cognitive point of view, research has shown that bilingual individuals tend to have better executive functions, such as the ability to focus, switch between tasks, and ignore distractions. Some studies even suggest that bilingualism may delay the onset of symptoms of Alzheimer''s disease and other forms of dementia. From a social and cultural perspective, speaking another language allows people to communicate with more individuals, access different cultural products and travel with greater autonomy. It also fosters tolerance and understanding, because learning a language often means learning about the people and customs associated with it. In professional terms, bilingual employees are usually in high demand, as companies operate in global markets and need staff who can negotiate and collaborate across borders. Despite these benefits, learning a new language is not always easy. It requires time, effort, practice and motivation. However, the long-term rewards far outweigh the challenges, both for individuals and for the societies in which they live. Encouraging bilingualism in schools and communities is therefore a valuable investment for the future.', '[{"pregunta":"Which cognitive benefit is mentioned?","opciones":["Better executive functions","Better eyesight","Taller growth","Faster heartbeat"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What condition might bilingualism delay?","opciones":["Flu","Alzheimer''s","Colds","Allergies"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Why do companies value bilingual employees?","opciones":["They work more hours","They operate in global markets","They eat less","They do not need holidays"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Is learning a language easy according to the text?","opciones":["Yes always","Not always but rewarding","No never","Impossible"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Origins of the Olympic Games', 'The Olympic Games have a fascinating history that stretches back more than two thousand years. The ancient Olympics began in 776 BC in the sanctuary of Olympia, in Greece. They were held every four years in honour of Zeus, the king of the Greek gods, and brought together athletes from different city-states who competed in events such as running, wrestling, discus, javelin, and chariot racing. Winners were celebrated as heroes and received olive wreaths. The ancient Games continued for almost twelve centuries before being banned in 393 AD by the Roman emperor Theodosius, who considered them to be a pagan festival. For nearly fifteen hundred years, the Olympic idea remained dormant until the end of the nineteenth century, when a French aristocrat called Pierre de Coubertin revived it. He believed that sport could promote peace, friendship and education among the peoples of the world, and in 1896 the first modern Olympic Games took place in Athens, with fourteen countries and less than three hundred athletes. Since then, the Games have grown enormously, now involving more than two hundred countries and over ten thousand athletes, and they include winter and summer editions as well as the Paralympic Games for athletes with disabilities. Despite political tensions and occasional controversies, the Olympic spirit, often summarised as excellence, friendship and respect, continues to inspire millions of people around the world.', '[{"pregunta":"When did the ancient Olympics begin?","opciones":["100 BC","776 BC","1000 AD","1896 AD"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Who banned the ancient Games?","opciones":["Julius Caesar","Theodosius","Augustus","Nero"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Who revived the modern Olympics?","opciones":["Napoleon","Pierre de Coubertin","Alexander","Churchill"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"How many countries participated in the first modern Games?","opciones":["Four","Fourteen","Fifty","One hundred"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Healthy Eating in the Modern World', 'In recent decades, the way people eat has changed dramatically in many parts of the world. The rise of fast food, ultra-processed products, and sugary drinks has contributed to a global increase in obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular diseases. At the same time, scientific research has confirmed that a balanced diet is one of the most important factors for long-term health. Nutritionists agree that a healthy eating pattern should include plenty of fruits and vegetables, whole grains, legumes, nuts, and moderate amounts of lean protein and healthy fats. The Mediterranean diet, typical of countries such as Spain, Italy and Greece, is often recommended because it is rich in these foods and has been linked to lower rates of heart disease and longer life expectancy. Drinking enough water and limiting the consumption of salt, sugar and saturated fats are also key recommendations. In addition to nutrition, the way we eat matters: slow meals eaten with family or friends tend to be more satisfying and healthier than quick snacks consumed alone in front of a screen. However, healthy eating is not only an individual choice. It depends also on the availability of good food, prices, advertising, and cultural habits. Governments, schools, and food industries all have responsibilities in creating environments where healthier choices are easier and more accessible to everyone in society.', '[{"pregunta":"Which diet is recommended in the text?","opciones":["Fast food","Mediterranean","High sugar","Low fibre"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What are people advised to limit?","opciones":["Vegetables","Water","Salt, sugar and saturated fats","Whole grains"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"Is healthy eating only an individual issue?","opciones":["Yes","No, it depends on many factors","Only for adults","Only for children"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What helps make meals healthier?","opciones":["Eating quickly","Eating in front of a screen alone","Eating slowly with family","Skipping meals"],"correcta":2}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Space Exploration: Past and Future', 'Space exploration is one of the most ambitious adventures in human history. It began in 1957, when the Soviet Union launched Sputnik, the first artificial satellite, opening the era of the so-called space race between the USSR and the United States. Just four years later, Yuri Gagarin became the first human to travel into space, followed in 1969 by the historic Apollo 11 mission, during which Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin walked on the Moon. In the decades that followed, both human and robotic missions explored the solar system. Probes have visited every planet, landing on Mars and providing stunning images of distant moons and asteroids. The International Space Station, continuously inhabited since 2000, allows astronauts from many countries to conduct scientific experiments in microgravity. In recent years, private companies such as SpaceX and Blue Origin have entered the field, developing reusable rockets and planning commercial flights to the Moon and Mars. Scientists are also working on ambitious projects such as the James Webb Space Telescope, which observes the universe in infrared light, and the search for exoplanets that could host life. Space exploration is expensive and faces many technical and ethical challenges, but it also pushes humanity to develop new technologies, inspires young generations, and reminds us of the fragility and uniqueness of our own planet.', '[{"pregunta":"What happened in 1957?","opciones":["Apollo 11","Launch of Sputnik","Yuri Gagarin''s flight","First woman in space"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Who walked on the Moon in 1969?","opciones":["Gagarin","Armstrong and Aldrin","Glenn","Shepard"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which company is mentioned as private?","opciones":["NASA","SpaceX","ESA","ISRO"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What does the James Webb Telescope observe?","opciones":["Ultraviolet","Infrared","X-rays","Radio waves"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Influence of Social Media on Teenagers', 'Social media platforms have become a central part of teenage life in the twenty-first century. Apps like Instagram, TikTok, and Snapchat allow young people to stay connected with friends, share their interests, and explore new ideas. For many teenagers, social media is not only a form of entertainment but also a source of news, inspiration, and self-expression. However, the impact of these platforms on teenage mental health and well-being is a subject of growing concern. Several studies suggest that excessive use of social media is linked to higher levels of anxiety, depression, and sleep problems. The constant comparison with carefully edited images of other people''s lives can damage self-esteem, and online harassment remains a serious issue. Moreover, the algorithms that decide which content appears in each user''s feed often prioritise emotional reactions and may create echo chambers in which users are only exposed to opinions similar to their own. On the other hand, social media can have positive effects: it allows teenagers to find communities that share their interests, to raise awareness about social and environmental issues, and to develop creative skills through photography, video editing, and writing. The key is to use these tools in a balanced way, being aware of the risks and taking advantage of the opportunities without letting the virtual world replace real-life relationships.', '[{"pregunta":"Which mental issue is linked to heavy social media use?","opciones":["Higher self-esteem","Anxiety and depression","Better sleep","Sharper focus"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What do algorithms sometimes create?","opciones":["Echo chambers","New friendships","Silent rooms","Better schools"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Which positive effect is mentioned?","opciones":["Less sleep","Finding communities with shared interests","Isolation","Ignoring news"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What is the suggested approach?","opciones":["Total ban","Balanced and aware use","Unlimited use","Random use"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Environmental Impact of Fast Fashion', 'Fast fashion refers to the quick production of cheap clothing inspired by the latest trends. Brands release new collections every few weeks, encouraging consumers to buy more and wear garments fewer times before discarding them. This business model has made fashion more accessible than ever, but it has also created significant problems for the environment and for society. The fashion industry is now considered one of the most polluting in the world. It uses enormous amounts of water, particularly for the production of cotton; it relies heavily on synthetic fibres derived from oil; and it generates huge quantities of textile waste, much of which ends up in landfills or is burned. In addition, fast fashion often depends on cheap labour in countries where workers face difficult and sometimes unsafe conditions, as tragic incidents like the collapse of the Rana Plaza factory in Bangladesh in 2013 painfully demonstrated. In response, an alternative movement known as slow fashion has emerged, promoting durable clothing made with respect for the environment and for workers. Consumers are encouraged to buy less, choose quality over quantity, repair their garments, and explore second-hand shops. Some companies are also starting to adopt more sustainable practices, such as recycling materials and using renewable energy. Changing the way we dress may seem small, but it can contribute to a more ethical and environmentally friendly global industry.', '[{"pregunta":"What is fast fashion?","opciones":["Handmade clothing","Quick production of cheap trendy clothing","Luxury haute couture","A running sport"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What happens to much textile waste?","opciones":["It is eaten","It ends up in landfills or is burned","It becomes gold","It is recycled 100%"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What happened at Rana Plaza in 2013?","opciones":["A fashion show","A factory collapse","A new collection","A protest march"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What does slow fashion promote?","opciones":["Buying more clothes","Durable and ethical clothing","Only luxury brands","Paper clothes"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Renewable Energy Revolution', 'In recent years, the world has witnessed a remarkable growth in renewable energy. Sources such as solar, wind, hydroelectric, and geothermal power are becoming increasingly important as countries try to reduce their dependence on fossil fuels and fight climate change. Solar panels, once considered expensive and inefficient, are now affordable and widely used, from rooftops on private houses to enormous solar farms in desert regions. Wind power has expanded rapidly, with giant turbines installed on land and offshore, capable of supplying electricity to thousands of homes. Hydroelectric power remains the oldest and one of the largest sources of renewable energy, while geothermal and tidal power are being developed to take advantage of natural resources in specific areas. The transition to renewables is not only environmentally important but also economically attractive, creating millions of jobs worldwide in manufacturing, installation, and maintenance. Challenges remain, however. Some renewable sources are intermittent: the sun does not always shine and the wind does not always blow, which means that efficient energy storage systems, such as advanced batteries, are essential. In addition, building the necessary infrastructure takes time and investment. Governments, businesses and citizens all have a role to play in this transition, and decisions taken in the coming decade will determine whether the renewable revolution succeeds in slowing climate change and meeting the energy needs of the future.', '[{"pregunta":"Which is NOT a renewable source in the text?","opciones":["Solar","Wind","Coal","Hydroelectric"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"Why are advanced batteries important?","opciones":["To store intermittent energy","To cook food","To heat houses only","To make phones"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What do renewables create economically?","opciones":["More pollution","Millions of jobs","Less infrastructure","Smaller cities"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Why is the transition urgent?","opciones":["To fight climate change","To sell more cars","To reduce holidays","To end democracy"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Cultural Diversity in Global Cities', 'Global cities like London, New York, Toronto, and Sydney are home to people from countless different backgrounds. Walking through their streets, one can hear many languages, smell food from around the world, and see religious buildings of different traditions standing side by side. This cultural diversity is the result of long histories of migration, driven by economic opportunities, wars, studies, or the search for a better life. Living in such diverse environments offers many advantages. It allows people to learn about other cultures, broaden their horizons, and challenge stereotypes. It also stimulates creativity and innovation, because ideas coming from different backgrounds often combine in surprising and productive ways. Cuisine, music, fashion and art frequently benefit from this mixing. However, cultural diversity also brings challenges. Integration is not always easy: newcomers may face language barriers, discrimination, or difficulties finding work or housing. Some communities worry that rapid changes could threaten their own traditions. To manage these tensions, cities have developed strategies such as intercultural education, community centres, language classes, and festivals that celebrate diverse heritages. When diversity is combined with respect and opportunity, it can become one of the greatest strengths of a city, contributing to its economic vitality, social richness and international reputation. Many experts believe that the ability to manage diversity successfully will be one of the key skills of societies in the decades to come.', '[{"pregunta":"Which is NOT given as a reason for migration?","opciones":["Economic opportunities","Studies","Seasons","Wars"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"How does diversity stimulate creativity?","opciones":["By isolating groups","By combining ideas from different backgrounds","By reducing contacts","By forbidding languages"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What challenges can newcomers face?","opciones":["Language barriers and discrimination","Free housing","No work","Easy life"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"What helps manage diversity in cities?","opciones":["Isolation","Intercultural education and events","Closing borders","Reducing schools"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Why Sleep Matters for Teenagers', 'Sleep is often described as the cornerstone of good health, yet many teenagers do not get enough of it. According to sleep specialists, young people between the ages of thirteen and eighteen need about eight to ten hours of sleep per night. In practice, however, many of them sleep much less, with serious consequences for their physical and mental well-being. Lack of sleep affects concentration and memory, making it harder to perform well at school. It also weakens the immune system and increases the risk of developing conditions such as obesity and depression. One of the main causes of sleep problems in adolescents is biological: during puberty, the release of melatonin, the hormone that regulates sleep, is naturally delayed, which makes teenagers fall asleep later in the evening. On top of this biological factor, lifestyle plays a significant role. Excessive use of smartphones and screens at night exposes teenagers to blue light that interferes with sleep. Caffeine, heavy homework loads, and early school start times also contribute to chronic sleep deprivation. Experts recommend several strategies to improve sleep: going to bed and getting up at regular times, avoiding screens at least one hour before bed, reducing caffeine in the afternoon, and creating a dark, quiet, and comfortable bedroom environment. Families and schools can also help by raising awareness of the importance of sleep and by giving teenagers realistic time to rest.', '[{"pregunta":"How many hours of sleep do teenagers need?","opciones":["4-5","6-7","8-10","12-14"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"Which hormone is delayed during puberty?","opciones":["Insulin","Melatonin","Cortisol","Adrenaline"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What interferes with sleep at night?","opciones":["Books","Blue light from screens","Music","Water"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which is NOT a recommended strategy?","opciones":["Drinking coffee at night","Avoiding screens before bed","Regular bedtimes","Dark bedroom"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Great Writers of the English Language', 'English literature is one of the richest in the world, with a long tradition of great writers whose works continue to be read and studied globally. Geoffrey Chaucer, who lived in the fourteenth century, is often called the father of English literature thanks to The Canterbury Tales, a collection of stories that offers a vivid picture of medieval society. William Shakespeare, writing at the end of the sixteenth and beginning of the seventeenth century, is perhaps the most famous English author of all time. His plays and sonnets explore themes of love, ambition, power, and human nature, and have been translated into countless languages. Jane Austen, in the early nineteenth century, gave the novel new heights with works like Pride and Prejudice, combining social critique with subtle humour. Charles Dickens, in the Victorian era, portrayed the realities of industrial London in novels such as Oliver Twist and Great Expectations. In the twentieth century, writers such as Virginia Woolf, George Orwell, and J.R.R. Tolkien opened new horizons in the novel, from the inner monologues of modernism to dystopian warnings and fantasy worlds. More recently, authors like Kazuo Ishiguro, a Nobel Prize winner, have continued this tradition with their reflections on memory and identity. Reading these writers not only offers pleasure but also provides insight into the societies and ideas of different centuries, making English literature a true treasure of world culture.', '[{"pregunta":"Who is called the father of English literature?","opciones":["Shakespeare","Chaucer","Dickens","Orwell"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Who wrote Pride and Prejudice?","opciones":["Austen","Brontë","Woolf","Eliot"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Which writer portrayed Victorian London?","opciones":["Tolkien","Orwell","Dickens","Ishiguro"],"correcta":2},{"pregunta":"Who won a Nobel Prize in literature recently?","opciones":["Ishiguro","Woolf","Shakespeare","Chaucer"],"correcta":0}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'Protecting Endangered Species', 'Thousands of animal and plant species around the world are at risk of extinction, and human activity is the main cause. Deforestation, pollution, climate change, illegal hunting and the expansion of agriculture destroy habitats and reduce biodiversity. The loss of a species is irreversible: once it is gone, it cannot be brought back. In addition, biodiversity is essential for the balance of ecosystems, which in turn support human life by providing food, medicines, clean water and fertile soils. In recent decades, many organisations have worked to protect endangered species. National parks and nature reserves offer safe environments where wildlife can live without being disturbed. International agreements such as the CITES convention regulate trade in wild animals and plants, making it harder for traffickers to profit from endangered species. Scientists also run breeding programmes for animals like the giant panda or the Iberian lynx, which have helped populations grow again. Local communities play a crucial role: when they benefit from eco-tourism or sustainable use of natural resources, they often become the best guardians of biodiversity. Citizens everywhere can help too, by supporting conservation organisations, reducing their ecological footprint, and making informed choices about the products they buy. Protecting endangered species is not only a moral duty towards other living beings but also a way of securing the health and prosperity of future human generations.', '[{"pregunta":"What is the main cause of species loss?","opciones":["Natural cycles","Human activity","Volcanoes","Sunspots"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What does CITES regulate?","opciones":["Ocean fishing quotas","Trade in wild species","Climate conferences","Airport taxes"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which species is mentioned as recovering?","opciones":["Dinosaur","Iberian lynx","Dodo","Mammoth"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Why is biodiversity important?","opciones":["It is not","It supports ecosystems and human life","Only for tourism","For decoration"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Power of Volunteering', 'Volunteering means giving time and effort to help others without expecting money in return. Around the world, millions of people take part in volunteer activities, from working in hospitals and schools to protecting the environment or assisting refugees. The motivations vary: some volunteer because of personal values, others to learn new skills or to gain experience, and many simply because they want to make a difference in their community. Studies show that volunteering has positive effects not only on the people who receive help but also on the volunteers themselves. Regularly helping others is linked to better mental health, greater life satisfaction and even lower risks of certain diseases. It can also improve employability, since volunteers often develop skills such as teamwork, leadership, communication and problem-solving. For young people, volunteering is a valuable way to discover career paths and understand social issues, while for older people it can provide a sense of purpose after retirement. Many governments and organisations promote volunteering through programmes that connect people with opportunities in their areas. Technology has also opened new possibilities, with online volunteering allowing people to contribute from anywhere in the world. However, it is important to volunteer in well-organised projects, because good intentions alone are not enough: without proper planning, help can sometimes produce unintended negative effects. When done responsibly, volunteering is one of the most powerful forms of active citizenship.', '[{"pregunta":"What does volunteering mean?","opciones":["Working for money","Giving time without pay to help others","Travelling for tourism","Studying languages"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Which is NOT a benefit mentioned?","opciones":["Better mental health","Higher salaries","More life satisfaction","Improved employability"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What has technology enabled?","opciones":["Online volunteering","Less need for help","Automatic donations","Silent volunteers"],"correcta":0},{"pregunta":"Why is good organisation important?","opciones":["To look official","To avoid unintended negative effects","To raise prices","To pay less tax"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb),

('ingles', 'bachillerato', '{1}', 'The Role of Critical Thinking Today', 'We live in an age of information overload, in which news, opinions, images and data reach us from countless sources at every moment. In this context, the ability to think critically has become more important than ever. Critical thinking is not simply about criticising; it means analysing information carefully, questioning assumptions, evaluating evidence and making reasoned judgements. It requires curiosity, open-mindedness and the willingness to change one''s view when faced with better arguments. Critical thinking is especially vital in the age of social media, where fake news, misleading images and manipulated statistics can spread very quickly. Without the habit of questioning what we read, we risk being deceived and making poor decisions in our personal, professional and civic lives. Schools and universities are increasingly incorporating critical thinking into their curricula, but it is a skill that must be practised throughout life. Some useful strategies include checking multiple sources, distinguishing facts from opinions, identifying the origin and purpose of information, recognising logical fallacies, and being aware of our own biases. Critical thinking does not mean being cynical or distrustful of everything; it means approaching information with intelligent scepticism and intellectual honesty. In democratic societies, where citizens must evaluate policies, debates and leaders, critical thinking is also essential for informed participation. It is, in short, one of the most valuable skills a person can develop in the twenty-first century.', '[{"pregunta":"What does critical thinking mainly require?","opciones":["Believing everything","Analysing and evaluating carefully","Ignoring sources","Complaining a lot"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Why is it especially important today?","opciones":["Because there is no information","Because of fake news and information overload","Because nothing is true","Because schools are closed"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"What is one suggested strategy?","opciones":["Trust only one source","Check multiple sources","Avoid reading","Ignore opinions"],"correcta":1},{"pregunta":"Does critical thinking mean being cynical?","opciones":["Yes always","No, it means intelligent scepticism","Sometimes","Only online"],"correcta":1}]'::jsonb);

